For the position of plane Mo. compares Auct. ad Herennium iv 20, 28 ‘non plane par' (where I should take uon with plone). On the other hand F. A. W. declares that ‘bene intendit uocem plane augetque eius uim.' Hand, Tursell. 11 p. 4, rejects plane as a gloss, but a gloss seems little likely here, and bene seems more likely as a gloss than plone. Possibly Cic. wrote bene et plone magnus3 a few inferior uss. have bene plone et magnus.

docem atomis: a cut at Epicurus’ atomic theory for which cf. i 11, arn. The idea occurred the more readily to Cic. as contemporary schools of philo· sophy took a very material view of the soul and its activities and experienceS. Zeller, Stoics, etc. pp. 198 foll, 429foll.

bonos utros: cf. ἓ 44 ‘uir optimus,’ n. and ref.; honest easy-going men, who had brought on gout by following Epi· curean rules of life.

crucientur: I think the subjunctive very doubtful. If sound we must take it with Kuh. as=qui cruciari se affirmant, but I entirely dissent from his assertion that by bonos uiros we must understand ei quorum uerbis fides haberi possit.
